ce:section.ce:para:
The prime hindrance for an efficient PDT is low tissue penetration by the light source employed. This can be overcome if the tissue penetration can be improved for deeper probing within the tumor by using more powerful radiations like X-ray. This concept of combining radiation and photodynamic therapy was first introduced by Chen and co-workers in 2006, and has been designated as PDTX [56,57],. The mechanism involves the generation of ROS via radiolysis which can destroy cancerous cell/ tissues. Upon exposure of X-rays water molecules produce various radical like hydroxyl radical (OH
), hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) and superoxide radical (O2
−). The production of such ROS can be exploited to induce a PDT effect when X-ray-tissue interaction produces singlet oxygen (1O2) Fig. 2 . However the process can be challenging in terms of producing an effective PDT while minimizing the negative effects on organs at risk. Experimental results demonstrate that a drastic reduction in the dose of X-ray (in Gray, Gy) can help to reduce this problem.
